Idea: Duolingo for K-12.

Skill Tree: allows you to see different skill trees like math, language arts, history, etc and have it be similar to games where you can explore your options, see what prereqs you need to fully understand the material, and give a brief glimpse of what that knowledge can help you do e.g. Linear Algebra is the basis of video game graphics, and after taking this class you can build simple graphics.

Leveling System: each "grade" is a level, 1st grade = level 1. Students only level up when they cover all the "minimum" skills for that level and then some # of experience points in skills/areas they like. This encourages students to explore areas they find cool, but also then allows them to learn 100% of the material before being forced to the next level. This leveling system can be broken down into monthly goals, weekly goals, daily goals, and there can be point reward systems involved. Key concept: 100% mastery learning, proper todos on how to approach these things, and customized goals per student

Community Hub: a portal for students where they can access help and connections with other students. Allows students to tap into a nation/global pool of mentors/helpers available.

Interactive Classes: This is the core essence of it all. Why should it matter how a student learns something? Whether by youtube video, book, video game or textbook, if they can demonstrate understanding then they should be able to use the tools available to them. We should encourage that by making systems to track and test their knowledge rather than try to force them into some standard box. This can be further strengthened by modern AI based recommendations systems. Rather than recommending things to purchase, or tiktoks to watch, let's use that technology to recommend the best learning tool for each student.

My pitch: So for background I'm in HS, I have a condition called Dysgraphia which is basically Dyslexia but for Handwriting (my handwriting is mostly unreadable). (pre-covid) Because of this I use a laptop, I've had quite a few friends say how they would like to use a laptop. This got me thinking, what software is out there for the notetaking and submitting tasks etc. I currently have a workflow where I write out the work in Notion and email the work manually. This takes time and annoys me a lot. I also have several other issues with Notion, I can't do diagrams, graphs or doodles (especially in science etc), getting images onto notion is a pain imo (I mostly will google for example Physics diagrams and c/p them), doing math is hard (I don't do math at all via laptop which sucks). So my pitch is to build a piece of software, which is a notebook style software with automatic submission for assignments. I seriously think over the next 5ish years there is going to be a shift to using laptops etc for day-to-day schoolwork. I kinda think it is the bastard lovechild of Notion and Google Classrooms. The MVP (yet to build due to having no time) is a notebook-software which auto emails a copy of the work to the teacher. I'll probably build this MVP even if I don't make it bigger, for my own amusement.
